The Pareto Funtier
Web3 is a vortex for talent, money, culture, and brainspace. I=E2=80=99ve b=
een trying to figure out why, and explain it in the simplest terms. I think=
 I have it, my tailwit explanation:
Web3 pushes out the Pareto Funtier.
Most of the decisions we make can be boiled down to fun and money.=C2=A0
Granted, that=E2=80=99s a gross oversimplification. I=E2=80=99m using =E2=
=80=9Cfun=E2=80=9D as a catch-all for a whole lot of things like love, mean=
ing, belonging, enjoyment, challenge, and more, and =E2=80=9Cmoney=E2=80=9D=
 as some sort of net present value (NPV) of resources acquired as a result =
of your decisions.=C2=A0
In my loose definition, going to church might count as fun because it gives=
 you meaning, or studying might count as money because it increases your ch=
ances of making more money later. Studying might also be fun if you enjoy i=
t and derive pleasure from the sense of challenge and accomplishment.=C2=A0
But the point here is to keep things simple, so we=E2=80=99ll go with those=
 two variables: fun and money.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s do some examples, using a 1-10 scale.=C2=A0
Reading a sci-fi book might be a 7 on fun and a 2 on money.=C2=A0
Reading a finance textbook might be a 2 on fun and a 6 on money.
Working in investment banking might be a 1 on fun and a 9 on money.=C2=A0
Working at a startup might be a 6 on fun and a 5 on money.=C2=A0
Blowing off work to watch your daughter=E2=80=99s soccer game might be an 8=
 on fun and a -1 on money.=C2=A0
Going to a rave is a 10 on fun and a 0 on money.=C2=A0
Taking out the trash is like a 0 on fun and a 0 on money, but some things y=
ou just need to do to be a functioning human being.=C2=A0
Going to an art museum is an 8 on fun and a 1 on money.=C2=A0
Playing a video game might be a 9 on fun and a 2 on money.=C2=A0
Scrolling Instagram might be a 7 on fun and a 0 on money.=C2=A0
Investing in a bond might be a 1 on fun and a 7 on money.=C2=A0
Investing in a restaurant might be an 8 on fun and a 2 on money.=C2=A0
Watching basketball is a 7 on fun and a 0 on money.
Being that friend who finds all the good music early is an 8 on fun and a 1=
 on money.
We=E2=80=99re glossing over nuance on the specifics here, too. A really exp=
ensive art museum with a terrible collection might be a 3 on fun and -1 on =
money. An online course that you=E2=80=99re taking purely to learn about so=
mething that fascinates you might be a 9 on fun and a 0 on money. A fast-gr=
owing startup with an electric culture solving a problem you want to solve =
might be an 8 on fun and a 9 on money.=C2=A0
Each example is also subject to each person=E2=80=99s preferences and situa=
tion. Reading sci-fi might be higher on the fun and money scale for me beca=
use on the fun side, I=E2=80=99m a nerd, and on the money side, maybe it sp=
arks an idea that helps me write something great. Some people genuinely enj=
oy working in investment banking. And each person has his or her own opport=
unity set =E2=80=93 that energetic, important, fast-growing startup might o=
nly hire people who are in the top 0.1% of people in their respective profe=
ssions.=C2=A0
Every decision overlaps, intersects, and influences the others. Maybe you c=
hoose to work in investment banking, sacrificing fun for money at work, bec=
ause you really want to live in a nice place today or because you want to r=
etire early and do only fun things thereafter.=C2=A0
And finally, that stone in the shoe of economists: humans aren=E2=80=99t as=
 rational as the textbooks would suggest. People often choose to do things =
that aren=E2=80=99t particularly fun or financially fruitful. Humans gonna =
human.=C2=A0
But assuming that we=E2=80=99ve baked everything in correctly, and accounte=
d for and discounted the future implications of our current decisions, for =
the sake of this thought exercise, we can say that humans make decisions in=
 such a way that maximizes fun and money.=C2=A0
You wouldn=E2=80=99t choose a job that=E2=80=99s a 2 on fun and a 3 on mone=
y when a job that=E2=80=99s a 3 on fun and a 5 on money is available to you=
=2E You could, however, choose among opti=
ons that add up to the same total fr=
om different angles. Jobs that are 2 on fun and 6 on money, 3 on fun and 5 =
on money, and 4 on both fun and money might be equally attractive. These eq=
ual choices are Pareto efficient.
Pareto efficiency [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uxCAMhU8zLCN-E7J=
g0U3XvQEi4GTQJJCC02luX2ayqGTZsi376X3eISy5nGbPFckrWTx3MAmedQVEKOSoUGwMhvVcCy=
VHEowMTCtNYrVzAdhcXA2WA8h-TGv0DmNO7wtKuSJ3MzDws5qEHic3UudV73s5e62pc1oxuHTdE=
SIkDwZ-oJw5AVnNHXGvN_Fx458tIHXP-Ig7hOi6XJY2evWtfLkCmC3Mc_SvJyeJhlPOGKc9E0pw=
2fGOT1rxeZBc9sL7gXe_lQqGj--bpNvCu3pMFZ1_dD5vpJiUccolpqWtH3e3wfpeNI-21e1IEU8=
LyU0rhMs-XhTfQOwCCUqjG6zDxk7oYdSaSc3Gy27jI-U4ci4kacoht6v0L_oHLrmKWQ] is =E2=
=80=9Ca situation where no individual or preference criterion can be better=
 off without making at least one individual or preference criterion worse o=
ff or without any loss thereof.=E2=80=9D In our example, you couldn=E2=80=
=99t get a job that=E2=80=99s 1 point more fun without giving up 1 point of=
 money. The Pareto frontier is the set of all Pareto efficient situations, =
it=E2=80=99s all the trade-offs that you might rationally be willing to mak=
e.=C2=A0=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re going to use Pareto Funtier here for a couple of reasons:=C2=
=A0
We=E2=80=99re talking about optimizing for a combination of money and fun, =
and the pun fits.=C2=A0
So that you=E2=80=99ll excuse me if I deviate a little from the precise def=
inition of Pareto efficiency. I=E2=80=99m just making a point. Lay off me, =
economists.=C2=A0
Anyway, in our case, the Pareto Funtier is the set of options at which you =
can=E2=80=99t have more fun without making less money or can=E2=80=99t make=
 more money without having less fun.=C2=A0
Given the existing options, it=E2=80=99s up to participants to choose among=
 options on the funtier based on their preferences, but economically speaki=
ng, they=E2=80=99re all fair trade-offs. If you want to make more money, yo=
u=E2=80=99ll have to give up a little fun. If you want to have more fun, yo=
u=E2=80=99ll need to give up a little money.=C2=A0
Which brings us back to why web3 is so attractive to so many, why once you =
go down the rabbit hole, it=E2=80=99s practically impossible to come out.=
=C2=A0
There are a lot of reasons =E2=80=93 technological, financial, psychologica=
l, emotional, and more =E2=80=93 that more and more people have been drawn =
to web3, but I think the simplest is this:
Web3 pushes the Pareto Funtier outwards by baking money into fun things and=
 fun into money things.=C2=A0
The people who argue that web3 is just a fad, or downright bullshit, by say=
ing that the user experience isn=E2=80=99t good or that there aren=E2=80=99=
t any =E2=80=9Creal use cases=E2=80=9D aren=E2=80=99t 100% wrong, they=E2=
=80=99re just missing the forest for the trees.=C2=A0
For early adopters, the user experience and use cases are good enough. Earl=
y adopters might be drawn to particular web3 projects because they=E2=80=99=
re a more fun way to make money than their job, or because they get to earn=
 money by doing things that they find fun anyway. As web3 grows, more use c=
ases emerge that are appealing to more people on one or both dimensions.=C2=
=A0
